<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="208" name="Hydrogen">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Hydrogen is the ____ element in the periodic table.</text>
            <option id="A">First</option><option id="B">Last</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Z = 1. Simplest atom.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydrogen shows dual behavior, resembling both ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkali metals , Halogens</option><option id="B">Alkali metals, Noble gases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electronic configuration ns1 (like alkali) and needs 1e- for octet (like halogens).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The most abundant element in the universe is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen</option><option id="B">Helium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Makes up ~70% of total mass of universe.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isotope of hydrogen with no neutrons is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Protium</option><option id="B">Deuterium</option><option id="C">Tritium</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common hydrogen (1H1).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isotope of hydrogen known as 'Heavy Hydrogen' is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Deuterium</option><option id="B">Protium</option><option id="C">Tritium</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Symbol D or 2H1. Contains 1 neutron.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radioactive isotope of hydrogen is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tritium</option><option id="B">Deuterium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Symbol T or 3H1. Beta emitter.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Laboratory preparation of Dihydrogen involves reaction of ____ with dilute HCl.</text>
            <option id="A">Granulated Zinc</option><option id="B">Copper</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Zn + 2H+ -> Zn2+ + H2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dihydrogen is commercially prepared by electrolysis of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acidified Water</option><option id="B">Brine solution</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses Platinum electrodes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>High purity hydrogen (>99.95%) is obtained by electrolysis of warm barium hydroxide solution using ____ electrodes.</text>
            <option id="A">Nickel</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Industrial process for very pure gas.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water-gas is a mixture of ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CO , H2</option><option id="B">CO2, H2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also called synthesis gas or syngas.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of steam with red hot coke is called ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Water-gas / Coal Gasification</option><option id="B">Decomposition</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C(s) + H2O(g) -> CO(g) + H2(g).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Syngas is used for synthesis of ____ and many hydrocarbons.</text>
            <option id="A">Methanol</option><option id="B">Ethanol</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basis of many industrial chemicals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Increasing H2 yield by reacting CO of syngas with steam is water-gas ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Shift</option><option id="B">Synthesis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>CO + H2O -> CO2 + H2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dihydrogen reacts with Nitrogen at high P/T over Fe catalyst to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammonia (NH3)</option><option id="B">Nitric acid</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Haber process.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Addition of hydrogen to unsaturated vegetable oils to form solid fats (vanaspati) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogenation</option><option id="B">Hydration</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses Nickel catalyst.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Binary compounds of hydrogen with other elements are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrides</option><option id="B">Oxides</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Categorized into ionic, covalent, metallic.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Saline or Ionic hydrides are formed with ____ block elements.</text>
            <option id="A">s-block</option><option id="B">p-block</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Active metals (except Be, Mg forming covalent).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Molecular or Covalent hydrides are formed with ____ block elements.</text>
            <option id="A">p-block</option><option id="B">s-block</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: CH4, NH3, H2O.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Metallic or Non-stoichiometric hydrides are formed with ____ block elements.</text>
            <option id="A">d and f block</option><option id="B">p-block</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydrogen fits in interstices.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electron-deficient hydride example: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">B2H6 (Diborane)</option><option id="B">CH4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Group 13 hydrides.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electron-precise hydride example: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CH4</option><option id="B">NH3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Group 14 hydrides.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electron-rich hydride example: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">NH3 (Has lone pair)</option><option id="B">CH4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Groups 15, 16, 17.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Amphoteric nature of water means it can act as both ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acid , Base</option><option id="B">Metal, Non-metal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can donate or accept protons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water is a liquid at room temp due to ____ bonding.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen</option><option id="B">Ionic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extensive association.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystalline form of water is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ice</option><option id="B">Vapor</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hexagonal structure usually.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hardness of water is due to presence of soluble salts of ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium , Magnesium</option><option id="B">Sodium, Potassium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specifically bicarbonates, chlorides, sulfates.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Temporary hardness is caused by ____ of Ca and Mg.</text>
